Question: A 37-year-old woman presents to her primary care physician with a 6-month history of fatigue. She denies any recent history of fevers, chills or headaches. She does not smoke or drink alcohol. A CBC demonstrates a microcytic anemia. Iron studies are ordered and demonstrate the following:
Serum iron: 40 µg/dL (normal 50–170 µg/dL);
TIBC: 230 µg/dL (normal 250–370 µg/dL);
Transferrin saturation: 10% (normal 15–50%);
Serum ferritin: 180 µg/L (normal 15-150 µg/L);
Which of the following is a likely cause of this patient's iron studies findings?
Options:
  A. Lead poisoning
  B. Dysfunctional uterine bleeding
  C. Splenic sequestration of RBCs
  D. Rheumatoid arthritis
Answer with a single letter (A, B, C, or D) only.
